    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-11-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-11-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <head>111. Record of Meeting<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d111fn1">Source:
                        Johnson Library, National Security File, Saunders Files, Aden &amp; South
                        Arabia, 4/1/66-1/20/69. Secret. Drafted by Acting Staff Director
                            <persName>John F. Buckle</persName> on November 17.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss>/NEA 67-47</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-11-16">November 16, 1967</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">INTERDEPARTMENTAL REGIONAL GROUP FOR NEAR EAST AND SOUTH ASIA</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Record of <gloss target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss>/NEA
                        Meeting—November 16, 1967</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The meeting was devoted to a further consideration of <hi rend="italic">our
                        policy towards South Arabia</hi>, in the light of the developments since the
                        <pb facs="0274" n="242" xml:id="pg_242"/>
                    <gloss target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss>/NEA meeting of July 26, 1967 (see <gloss
                        target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss>/NEA 67-24, 7/26/67, for a record of agreements
                    reached at that time).<note n="2" xml:id="d111fn2">
                        <ref target="#d100">Document 100</ref>.</note> The Group:</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Reviewed</hi> recent significant developments in the rapidly
                    moving situation as noted in the paper prepared for the meeting by the Country
                    Director (<gloss target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss>/NEA 67-43)<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d111fn3">
                        <ref target="#d110">Document 110</ref>.</note> and as elaborated by him.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Agreed</hi> that, although our previous tentative planning
                    with respect to an independent South Arabia might prove to be basically valid,
                    there was now more reason to be concerned regarding the viability of the
                    emerging government than anticipated last July and we should be convinced that
                    the government in power was going to be able to govern successfully and intended
                    to honor its international obligations before we extended our recognition.
                    Should we decide to do so, we might prefer initially to establish our mission at
                    the Charge level. In this connection, the Group agreed that we should keep in
                    close consultation with the British and the Saudi Arabians both regarding their
                    assessments of the new government as it emerges and their intentions towards
                    it.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Agreed</hi> that we should certainly not be ahead of the
                    British in the matter of recognition and would also look for prior action by
                    some of South Arabia’s regional neighbors. The Saudi attitude would be important
                    but her decision not to recognize would not necessarily cause us to withhold
                    recognition.</p>
                <list>
                    <head>MEMBERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>Executive Chairman—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BLD2">Battle</persName>
                    </item>
